# crm_lots_agents — frontend conventions

Stack: **React**, **MUI**, **Redux** (global app state), centralized HTTP (no raw axios in components), **i18n** for user-visible strings.

## Feature-first layered architecture

**Primary axis is the feature**, not the technical layer. New work lives under `src/features/` (and registers in `src/app/store.ts` when it needs Redux).

### Layout

| Area | Role |
|------|------|
| **`src/features/<domain>/`** | Top-level domain (e.g. `customers`, `payments`, `dashboard`). |
| **`src/features/<domain>/<sub-feature>/`** | Screen or workflow inside the domain (e.g. `customers/customers-list`, `payments/verify-payments`). Use nested folders when a domain has multiple independent surfaces. |
| **`src/app/`** | App shell only: **`router.tsx`**, **`store.ts`**, **`axios.ts`** / HTTP entry, **`hooks.ts`**, **themes**, and **shared** components/models/services used across many features. |
| **`src/views/`** | Legacy route wrappers that compose features. **Prefer** importing feature entry components from `src/features/...` in `router.tsx` directly; add new thin wrappers here only when matching existing patterns. |

### Layers inside a feature (colocate by concern)

Use **consistent folder names** within a feature so related code stays together. Not every feature has every layer — add only what the feature needs.

| Layer | Typical folder / files | Contents |
|-------|-------------------------|----------|
| **Routes / entry** | `pages/`, `*-view.tsx`, `*-page.tsx` | Route-mounted components. **Keep these thin**: composition only (see “Page components” below). |
| **UI** | `components/` | Sections, dialogs, tables; split by section/subsection into separate files. |
| **State (server-backed)** | `slice/`, `store/`, `*.slice.ts`, `redux/` | Redux slice(s), selectors, thunks for this feature. Register reducers in **`src/app/store.ts`**. |
| **API** | `services/` | Feature-specific calls built on the shared HTTP client (`src/app/axios.ts` or existing service modules), not ad-hoc `fetch` in components. |
| **Pure logic / types** | `business-logic/`, `domain/`, `types/` | Mappers, rules, TypeScript types, or non-UI helpers that belong to the feature. |

**Order of dependency (allowed direction):** UI → Redux / hooks → services → shared `app` utilities. **Do not** import feature components from `src/app` except via the usual shell (router, store, axios).

### New feature checklist

1. Create **`src/features/<domain>/[<sub-feature>/]`** with `components/`, and `slice/` (or co-located `*.slice.ts`) plus `services/` when the feature talks to the API.
2. Add routes in **`src/app/router.tsx`** pointing at a **thin** page/view under the feature.
3. Register any new reducer in **`src/app/store.ts`**.
4. Add **i18n** keys for new copy; reuse **shared** models under `src/app/models/` when the shape is global, or **`types/`** inside the feature when local.

## Page components (route-level / `*Page` shells)

- **Do not** connect the page shell to Redux: avoid `useSelector`, `useDispatch`, and `useStore` in the file that defines the route’s top-level page component.
- **Do not** hold **feature or server-backed** state with `useState` / `useReducer` in the page shell. The page should **compose** smaller components and pass **only** what is needed for layout or stable IDs (e.g. route params forwarded as props).
- **Exception:** trivial **UI-only** state that exists solely to coordinate layout chrome (e.g. “drawer open”) may live on the page **only** if it does not duplicate or shadow Redux-backed data and stays minimal; prefer pushing even that into a small child component when it grows.

## Redux and re-renders

- **Server / backend data** belongs in Redux (slices, thunks, RTK Query — whatever the feature already uses). Treat the store as the source of truth for **fetched** and **shared** domain data.
- **Subscribe at the smallest component that needs the data.** Avoid wiring a large parent to Redux when only a small subtree changes; connect the **leaf** (or a narrow section component) so only that subtree re-renders when the slice updates.
- The app uses Redux for views; **prefer** localized subscriptions over lifting subscriptions to page-level wrappers.

## Local state vs Redux

- **Local state** (`useState`, etc.): drafts, focus, open/close of dialogs, form fields **before** submit, purely client UI — anything that **must not** be sent to the backend or shared globally.
- **Redux:** data **loaded from** or **synced with** the backend, shared across sections, or needed for navigation and reporting consistency.
- **Exception:** when colocating state in Redux would hurt performance or cause unnecessary global updates, keep data local or use memoized selectors in a **small** component — document the intent briefly in code comments only when non-obvious.

## File structure (avoid huge files)

- Split route pages into **one file per main section** (e.g. `CustomerDetailHeader.tsx`, `CustomerDetailAssignments.tsx`).
- If a section has **subsections**, give each subsection its **own** file (nested folders are fine).
- Prefer **composition** and **named exports** consistent with the rest of the feature folder.

## HTTP and strings

- Use the shared HTTP layer / API modules — **no** raw axios (or ad-hoc `fetch`) inside presentational components unless the codebase already establishes a different pattern for that feature.
- All user-visible copy goes through **i18n** keys.

